\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Desert or desart in their reports -f rom Latin adjective desertus, past participle of dererere: to abandon.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Europeans had no real conception of the world\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s dry deserts until they started going to them. Look at the paintings of St. Antony. It was not only that vegetation was a requisite compositional device, the sheer sparsity of the Egyptian desert was as beyond imagining as the moon. Scarcely any of these paintings are without trees, and many show the abbot sitting primly in a landscape as lush as the apenninines in spring. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Felix Fabri - dominican friar: Firstly, this country is called the desert because it seems to be, so to speak, deserted by god, as though god had used it to improve or adorn the rest of the universe\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8230\'85 Secondly, this country is called the lonesome place, because no one longs for that land\u8230\'85 Thirdly, this country iscalled the solitary place, because it is unfrequented by men. It is solitary because none of the countries which lie round about it wish to have any connection with or likeness to that land.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 He goes on to tell that the desert is the image of death, that nothing grows there, that it is waterless, salt, pathless, inhabited only by serpents, scorpions, dispades ( a kind of snake whose bite causes intolerable thirst), worms, dragons, fauns, and satyrs; a place of demonic temptation, where great merit isacquired, and where lthe laws and commandments were given.}
