\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 It is the saguaros giant candelabra forms that break the line of each hillside and provide landmarks. The tallest for kilometers stands beside the cabin. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Rinon mountains, the Little Rincons before.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 A blade of light drops from the distant peaks of the rincons, down the foothills and towards me across the alluvial plain, until slowly, like a lava flow, the threshold where light meets shadow approaches the cabin - and then: there! The warmth as teh sun\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s rays touch the back of my head and my shadow is thrown down long before me.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The ridge separates two washes (dry, except after cloudbursts): one is broad and shallow, the other is deep and narrow and what they call an arroyo }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Book about the dangerous animals of the region, every one hair-triggered, you\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92d be forgiven for inferring, to sting you, bite you, mal you, or char with its fier breath. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Sleeps outside because of the noise that lizards in the roof make. Noise of the desert subsumes it.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 I lift each of the bed\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s feet and slip containers of water under them - tin mugs, a wooden saucer, a saucepan - to keep conenose kissing-bugs or scorpions from joining me. I position the two chairs beside the bed, one at the foot, one alongside my head, and stand lanterns on them.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Place scented candles around you, in the mornings the hardened wells around their wicks are black with flying insects. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Most afternoons, as teh warmth first intensifies like an oven preheating, then levels off at a temperature that permits nothing but sitting in the cabin\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s shadow cowled in a we scarf:}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Monks filter into an abbey. \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93I stood at the back and listened to their plainsong.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The Desert Fathers, the third- and fourth century solitaires of Upper Egypt, and the first of them, St. Antony. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 St. Antony and St. Paul and a loaf of bread.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 When St. Antony left his home, the young man retired alone to a hut in the desert - bit it wasn\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92t far, hardly the true desert at all, just a place outside the village walls. There he was besieged by the devil\u8217\'92s temptations: memories of his former comforts, his abandoned sister, the promise of money and glory, and above all the \u8220\'93spirit of fornication.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93In the bole of a dead tree.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 He traveled still further into the desert, deeper into the devil\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s domain, like a military scout preceding an invasion. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93By now he has become an iconic figure and must fend off acolytes as well as demons. He travels still deeper into the desert, until he reaches the place that would be his home for the rest of his life: the foothills of the south galala mountains. This story of a step-by-step progression into oblivion, from the lush Nile floodplain to the arid interior, became a model for others wishing to renounce society. According to St. Athanasius, \u8220\'93 cells filled with holy bands of men who said psalms, loved reading, fasted, prayed, rejoiced in the hope of things to come, laboured in almsgiving and preserved love and harmony, one with the other.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Even among the women, the metaphor of sexual conquest was near-ubiquitous: time and again the feminised desert was unveiled, exposed, vanquished and finally penetrated. My bedding was dusty with dried binding-glue. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 For geographoers, deserts are simply places where the average annual rainfall is less than 250 millimeteres, and where precipitation, by rain or fog or dew, is exceeded by potential evapotranspiration (evaporation and the transpiration of plants). The aridity index four categories of drylands:  Hyper-arid, arid, semi-arid, and sub-humid. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The model desert journey is a progression from the sub-humid to the hyper-arid, from the Nile to the \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Inner Mountain,\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 In the Vitae Patrum, the collected sayings and biographies of the Desert Fathers, published in the seventeenth century, we learn of the paneremos: at once the place of uttermost lifelessness, and teh locus where the desert\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s identity was most purely asserted, and that point furthest from the periphery. Polar explorers have another term: the Pole of Maximum Inaccessibility. This it seemed was the ultimate objective of every desert traeller: the axis where the absolute coexists with the infinite. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 A depression the size of France, occupying a third of the Arabian Peninsula, the Empty Quarter is bounded to the north\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8230\'85. THis tremendous bowl of sand has been stirred, clockwise for perhaps two million years, by two great winds: the shamal that sweeps across the arabian gulf from Iraq, and the Kharif that brings the south-west monsoon to soak Dhofar. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Rub\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92 Al-Khali - none have ever crossed the heart of it. It is a name of terror throught rbia. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Two kinds of tribes: those who you have a blood feud with, and those who dont. Both want your camels and arms, the second want your life as well.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 It hs become difficult to be a pioneer. THe world has been done. THere are only the adventurers now, this new breed of fanatic: rangy large-toothed guys seeking not knowledge or even territory but novelty, managed suffering, \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Experience\u8221\'94, mterial, sponsorship - K2 by canoe, the Amazon by bike, the North Pole on stilts. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 A brief catlike rigidifying, then the recovery of sangfroid.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i0 I could feel his breath on my eyeballs - breathing the same air.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 We had left the peripheral gravel plains behind. Underfoot was a floor of cracked white clay dusted with red sand. Between us and the mountainous pink dunes that fomred the horizon were only two salt bushes, long dead. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 As Nigel spoke, the realisation was dawning on me that I would die if Hassan, our guide, did not return. Never before had I known so intensely my life\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s dependence on another. It was as if I had been dosed with poison whose antidote he alone possessed. And where was Hassan?}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \fi360\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Rolling scrolls of circulation (wind) are known as Hadley Cells.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Deserts in equator, but als, Along the western coasts of the continents, se winds cool the air, reducing its capacity to hold moisture and preventing the formation of clouds, contributing to the creation of \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8216\'91coastal\u8217\'92 deserts such as Chile\u8217\'92s Atacama and southern Africa\u8217\'92s Namib. This effect is amplified in the southern hemisphere by the influence of anti-clockwise ocean gyres, which carry cold water to the west coasts of the continents. Meanwhile, winds arriving from the east have surrendered any moisture to the parched land. Moreover, the sheer remoteness and size of many deserts - thos of australia and central asia - mean that vapour from the sea simply can\u8217\'92t reach them. So dryness is partly a factor of isolation. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 In Oman fertile land exists in two thin strips: the arable corridor of Batinah, which runs north-west from Muscat; and in the south the Dhofar coastal plain, where Salalah lies\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8230\'85 When air confronts a ountain range, such s the jabl Qara, it cools as it climbs, forming rainclouds that sap its moisture. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 We entered the nejd, a rubbled karstland dissected by broad wadis that had not run for generations and scattered with cement-coloured bergs of limestone. Pink sand had been banked along the road\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s eastern verge by last night\u8217\'92s winds.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The alluvial boulders strewing the hamadah became rocks; the rocks became smaller black nodules of basalt, laid down in rows upon the paler grit as if by a harrow. THe land had been progressively degraded, growing flatter and smoother as it became drier.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Hasan was from a mountain tribe. He had a neat black beard and a steady, strategising gaze of  the kind I associate with both artists and military men\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8230\'85 He wore a white headcloth, and a white dishdasha, grease-fingered across its front. ON his feet were perished black rubber sandals. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Dust devils shimmied in the middle distance. You blinked and they\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92d vanished. In the heat-haze the horizon lifted like a page in a draught. For eighty kilometeres just these gavel plains, more relentless in their aridity than even the Empty Qurter\u8217\'92s heart. At least in the Sands, for Bertram Thomas and his retinue, there had been occasional waterholes; here, for camel-days, there would be nothing, not so much as a frond of ailing saltbush, and no shelter for anything bigger than an invertebrate.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 There had been a quiet sifting of the land as we\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92d dropped down from the mountains: solid to particulate, coarse to smooth, hard to soft; almost indiscernable.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 A boulder warmed will expand; cooling it will contract. Repeated over a hundred thousand days and nights, the opposing pressures will begin to undo the rock\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s integrity. Tiny fractures will appear and widen; in high-altitude deserts frost will enter these cracks and jemmy them apart; salt will seep into the rocks as a solution and in crystallising expand the cracks still further (a process known as salt-jacking). The boulder thus divides and subdivides, spalling and flaking and crumbling, and with the wind and water, the pieces will be dispersed. And so mountains become boulders, and boulders rocks, and rocks stons, then gravel, shingle, grit sand - ultimately, dust. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Rising from the plains, the dunes were visible from twenty kilometers away. After the hours of ash-like grey and pale cracked clay, it was as if we were nearing a new reality, one that seemed as gorgeous and auspicious, from afar, as the world of dreams. Here was a place for a checkpoint, I thought, a true border. I sensed Hassan\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s relief. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 From the desert\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s edge, crescent dunes no bigger than whales encroached on to the plain like scouts sent ahead of a vast school clamouring to their rear. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Religious ablution (ritual washing)}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 We entered the dunes and almost instantly it was impossible to tell in which direction lay the plains we had just come across. To one lost in a maze, teh outer passages are indistinguishable from the interior. I was reminded that one of the Arabic words for desert is a synonym of labyrinth. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The dunes at the desert\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s edge were beach-size, but kilometere by kilometee their stature grew. It was like nothing I had experienced save for being at sea. As if hassan were piloting a skiff over choppy straits, our path up and down the dunes assumed a rhythm: a pass identified; a roar of acceleration; then the momentary sensation of equivocation on the wind stropped cresst, before the sudden plumet. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 After an hour we found Mohammed\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s Land Cruiser in the centre of a flat rink of gypsum. Soran the camel was couched nearby. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Under the seat of his Land Cruiser he kept a ceremonial sword, which he would sometimes unsheathe and, with a glance to ensure you were watching, throw spearlike into a dune.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 So loved was Mohammed by Soran that the mere sound of his vehicle approaching would send the camel into groans of exaltation. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 I clambered barefoot to teh summit of a tall dune nearby. It took twenty minutes. The sand under my soles was losing its warmth, as if life were abandoning it. Like a pond it was cool beneath the surface. From there, maybe thirty meteres up, the desert laid out before me was brinkless, its coulours shifting by the second as the sun went down; but its vastness was not of the sublime kind that induces unease. The scale wasn\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92t belittling, because one had no sense of one\u8217\'92s own size in proportion to it. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Camels\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92 night vision, Mohammed told me, is exceptional. \u8220\'93If your camel looks slowly left to right, it is a fox. If your camel stops chewing and stares into the darkness, something is wrong.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Soran was yellow, with a dark bushy hackle along his spine, smaller than the all-black brutes loitering alongside the road from Thumrait. He wore a smile of beatific forbearance, and was the object of lavish tenderness on the part of Hassan and Mohammed - tenderness born of respect, even love. They would no more shout at or beat him than they would the sagest of grandfathers. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The main quality sought in a desert campsite, other than shade from the sun as it rises, is shelter from the wind. It\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s thought that most of the dunes accumulated some million years ago, during the Late Quaternary period, when winds even stronger than today\u8217\'92s winnowed sand from both the wadis of the peninsula\u8217\'92s interior and the Arabian Gulf. The wind continues to be a potent presence: it shapes and reshapes the dunes, and , during the day, is as constant as the sun. The sun heats the morning sands, the warm air rises and must be replaced. Hence the wind ubiquitous in desert literature. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Army sent to vanquish the lord of the desert wind. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Bertram Thomas: story of a party of the Mahra tribe who pursued a band of camel raiders into a part of the desert unknown to them, only for a wind to rise and obliterate the tracks they had been following. \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Six months later one of my own party of rashidis came upon the seven skeletons and the bones of their camels.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 THe desert is mobile and wind its engine. The wind shapes the dunes. To travel in the Empty Quarter is to see their forms - \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93species\u8221\'94, as they are known - in their infinite permutations. The desert is formed chiefly of the uruq variety (from the arabic \u8216\'91vein\u8217\'92 ), towering parallel ridges sometimes tens of kilometers long, and crescenet-shaped barchans(From \u8220\'93horn\u8221\'94), whose tips point in the direction of the prevailing wind. But few deserts, even the great ergs or \u8220\'93sand seas\u8221\'94 of the Sahara, ar forme dof sand alone. In the southern marches you experience not a pure dune-land, an endless beach, but a rather a complex of arenas. THe sand is quartz; anything softer will be ground to dust and blown away. Each surface grain accumulates a rind of ferric oxide, and it is this that accounts for the arabian dune\u8217\'92s characterisitic redness. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The dunes are spearated by Shuquq, interdune corridors - elongated plaines of brown gravel and white gypsum; while the dunes are barriers exahausting to man, camel, and vehicle alike, these flat plains are the desert\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s highways. From their edges archaologist have recovered the bones of water buffalo, the shells of freshwater molluscs, and the teeth of hippopotami. For, some twenty five-thousand years ago, during a cold phase, these plains were lakes. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 IT was where the sand melded into a gypsum plain that two ravens came to inspect me, as I was walking alone the following morning, soon after dawn.}
